description:
This is a still image from video footage of it walking down those steps and out.

A story about another observation that I don't have any footage from. This was about the year I was down at the Hyatt beach around 3am on a different night. I had an amazing experience. I observed a black bear walk along the east side of Lone Eagle Grill (before it was all gated off), all the way out on the Hyatt pier, climb down into the water, swim around playing out in the moonlit water. It was maybe fishing off the pier too because I have seen some large fish off the pier at night. It swam all the way across the buoy line distance over to the other side of the beach near where Incline Creek comes out. The experience lasted about an hour or so. What amazing imagery to imagine a time when wildlife like this had easy access to the lake.
It's upsetting that the Hyatt continually blocks off more access to the wildlife and locals with more gates, walls, and fences over their greed. More recently building that eye sore of a beach bar. What was once a beautiful open beach from a fire pit is now a development.

This dumpster and bakery just inside those doors was a problem for years. I wouldn't doubt that it still is. I had researched and proposed to them to install an automatic sliding door that was set to a timer to switch to manual operation at night. No different than grocery stores. It would have saved them a lot of money on air conditioning, heating, bears walking into the bakery and made it easier on employees. They ignored my proposal though.

description:
Found on a well decayed log.

More of these small unknown Crepidotus found up there in a damp seepage area. I left these out overnight, until the gills became tan, to make sure I could get some spores. Maybe I’ll be able to get a species on these this time.

Ok, this one has been bothering me for awhile, about a year and half or so…

But these are small, and pure white, sessile on wood, and just looks like yet another Crepidotus. But it was kinda funny under the scope.

The micro-shot is of spores from the gill at 1000x in Meltzer’s. Here the spores are ellipsoid, and more or less hyaline, and no reactions with the Meltzer’s. But the spores are clearly longitudinally striate here.

With that sort of spore ornamentation I thought it might be easy enough to come up with. But it didn’t show up in the Crepidotus monographs, or other Crepidotus info, so that was just bothering me.

But with the spore striation it should be Clitopilus, but I could find much on Clitopilus info, that might give me more info on a sessile form. So, I tabled it. But then I got Funga Nordica recently, and for some reason I thought of this one, and thought what would Funga Nordica say? And in their Clitopilus key there are a few sessile forms listed, and a couple that are white. Using that key, I get a suggestion of Clitopilus hobsonii.

I also found on the web from Upstate New York, there was a Clitopilus key of sessile forms:

http://www.nybg.org/bsci/res/hall/clitokey.html

So, this looks pretty good. These aren’t some funny Crepidotus, but they really are a Clitopilus. Pretty cool.

description:
Flew into a neighbors window to provide Mono County's second confirmed record. I promptly prepared it into a specimen and provided it to the LA County Museum of Natural History collection. Skull <10% ossified and pointy recs indicate young bird.
My neighbor had it in her freezer for a year, and didn't know the exact date she found it, except late fall of 2008. She thought most of the leaves were off the trees, which suggests November, but this is very tentative. 
Accepted by California Bird Records Committee. Being a dead bird I enter it here rather than eBird.

description: When we found these, I was imagining they were young porcini. Dark, nut-brown caps, white stems, small pale pores, mild, woodsy taste, growing under pine near grass, but... the slightly viscid caps and relatively even, narrow stalks gave me pause. I bagged them, brought them home, and tried stepping through the keys in MD, which lead me to Suillus brevipes, the Short-stemmed Slippery Jack. The latter is also supposedly fine eating, but it's good to know the difference. S. brivepes will grow in clusters, has smooth, unreticulate stalk, and a viscid cap. The flesh is firm like fresh Boletus and unlike many other Suillus, which I think played into my confusion.

First the First: First Dicamptodon I've ever seen. First the Second: First time I've heard a salamander vocalize! While getting pleasantly lost in the woods, I came upon a stream bed with some promisingly flat stones. I've been itching to find one of the giant salamanders pretty much ever since I moved out here, and lo and behold, after a few rocks, I found this fine specimen. And what did it do upon discovery? It croaked! Not metaphorically, but literally, and repeatedly! Joy! Note: the colors are a bit off here, probably due to using an LED head lamp as a light source. It was actually more tan than purple. I should probably invest in a flash.
